{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.4.0"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceId":115336,"databundleVersionId":13766970,"sourceType":"competition"}],"dockerImageVersionId":30749,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"r","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/xinyunchoong/group07-teo-aada-xy?scriptVersionId=263813293\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Introduction\n\nIn this project we predicted physical activity from signals. \n\n**Data**\nSignals are sequences of measurements that change over time. In this project, signals were measured using a smartphone accelerator and a gyroscope. We wanted to predict three static postures (standing, sitting, lying) and three dynamic activities (walking, walking downstairs and walking upstairs) as well as postural transitions from epochs from signal data. We will explain epochs below.\n\n**Features**\nIn order to recognize patterns from signals, we extracted time-domain and spectral-domain features from signals. We explain out reasoning behind our feature signals below. \n\n**Model**\nwe used Linear Discriminant Analysis (lda), k-Nearest Neighbors (knn) model and the Multinomial Logistic Regression (mlr) model to make predictions based on our features.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Importing Data ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"library(tidyverse) \noptions(width=100) \n\nsystem(paste0(\"cp -r \", list.files(\"../input\", full.names=TRUE), \"/* ./\"))\n\n# Train and Test folder are located in the RawData folder\nlist.files(\"../input/RawData\")\n\n# The Train folder contains 85 files:\nlength(list.files(\"./RawData/Train\"))\n\n# A sample of the file names in the Train folder; notice the filename pattern\nset.seed(1)\nsample(list.files(\"./RawData/Train\"),6)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-24T18:02:02.861422Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-24T18:02:02.901467Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-24T18:02:06.782056Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-24T18:02:06.780171Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stderr","text":"── \u001b[1mAttaching core tidyverse packages\u001b[22m ──────────────────────── tidyverse 2.0.0 ──\n\u001b[32m✔\u001b[39m \u001b[34mforcats  \u001b[39m 1.0.0     \u001b[32m✔\u001b[39m \u001b[34mreadr    \u001b[39m 2.1.5\n\u001b[32m✔\u001b[39m \u001b[34mggplot2  \u001b[39m 3.5.1     \u001b[32m✔\u001b[39m \u001b[34mstringr  \u001b[39m 1.5.1\n\u001b[32m✔\u001b[39m \u001b[34mlubridate\u001b[39m 1.9.3     \u001b[32m✔\u001b[39m \u001b[34mtibble   \u001b[39m 3.2.1\n\u001b[32m✔\u001b[39m \u001b[34mpurrr    \u001b[39m 1.0.2     \u001b[32m✔\u001b[39m \u001b[34mtidyr    \u001b[39m 1.3.1\n── \u001b[1mConflicts\u001b[22m ────────────────────────────────────────── tidyverse_conflicts() ──\n\u001b[31m✖\u001b[39m \u001b[34mdplyr\u001b[39m::\u001b[32mfilter()\u001b[39m masks \u001b[34mstats\u001b[39m::filter()\n\u001b[31m✖\u001b[39m \u001b[34mdplyr\u001b[39m::\u001b[32mlag()\u001b[39m    masks \u001b[34mstats\u001b[39m::lag()\n\u001b[36mℹ\u001b[39m Use the conflicted package (\u001b[3m\u001b[34m<http://conflicted.r-lib.org/>\u001b[39m\u001b[23m) to force all conflicts to become errors\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"","text/markdown":"","text/latex":"","text/plain":"character(0)"},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"85","text/markdown":"85","text/latex":"85","text/plain":"[1] 85"},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"<style>\n.list-inline {list-style: none; margin:0; padding: 0}\n.list-inline>li {display: inline-block}\n.list-inline>li:not(:last-child)::after {content: \"\\00b7\"; padding: 0 .5ex}\n</style>\n<ol class=list-inline><li>'gyro_exp43_user21.txt'</li><li>'acc_exp58_user29.txt'</li><li>'acc_exp01_user01.txt'</li><li>'acc_exp53_user26.txt'</li><li>'gyro_exp01_user01.txt'</li><li>'acc_exp23_user11.txt'</li></ol>\n","text/markdown":"1. 'gyro_exp43_user21.txt'\n2. 'acc_exp58_user29.txt'\n3. 'acc_exp01_user01.txt'\n4. 'acc_exp53_user26.txt'\n5. 'gyro_exp01_user01.txt'\n6. 'acc_exp23_user11.txt'\n\n\n","text/latex":"\\begin{enumerate*}\n\\item 'gyro\\_exp43\\_user21.txt'\n\\item 'acc\\_exp58\\_user29.txt'\n\\item 'acc\\_exp01\\_user01.txt'\n\\item 'acc\\_exp53\\_user26.txt'\n\\item 'gyro\\_exp01\\_user01.txt'\n\\item 'acc\\_exp23\\_user11.txt'\n\\end{enumerate*}\n","text/plain":"[1] \"gyro_exp43_user21.txt\" \"acc_exp58_user29.txt\"  \"acc_exp01_user01.txt\"  \"acc_exp53_user26.txt\" \n[5] \"gyro_exp01_user01.txt\" \"acc_exp23_user11.txt\" "},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":2},{"cell_type":"code","source":"act_labels = read.table(\"activity_labels.txt\", header=FALSE, col.names=c('code','activity'))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-24T18:02:06.784943Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-24T18:02:06.786552Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-24T18:02:06.799516Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-24T18:02:06.79773Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":3},{"cell_type":"code","source":"labels0 = read_delim(\"./RawData/Train/labels_train.txt\", delim=\" \", \n                    col_names = c('trial', 'userid', 'act_code', 'start', 'end'), col_types=\"iiiii\")\n\nlabels = labels0 |> left_join(act_labels, by=c(act_code = \"code\"))\n\n# file path\nfilename <- \"RawData/Train/acc_exp01_user01.txt\"\n\n# extract parts of the filename\nusername <- str_extract(filename, \"(?<=user)\\\\d+\") |> as.integer()\nexpname  <- str_extract(filename, \"(?<=exp)\\\\d+\") |> as.integer()\n\n# import the data\nuser01 <- read_delim(filename, delim = \" \", col_names = FALSE, col_types = \"ddd\")\n\nsample_labels <- labels |>\n  mutate(segment = row_number()) |>         # identify each separate activity interval\n  reframe(\n    sampleid = seq.int(start, end),          # expand start:end into all sample IDs\n    .by = c(trial, userid, act_code, activity, segment)\n  )\n\nuser_df = \n  tibble(userid = username, trial = expname, sampleid = seq.int(0, nrow(user01) - 1)) |>\n  bind_cols(user01) |>\n  left_join(sample_labels, by = c(\"userid\", \"trial\", \"sampleid\"))\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-24T18:02:06.802421Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-24T18:02:06.803965Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.189664Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.187902Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":4},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"As computers can only reflect signals in discrete samples, we have split the continuous timeframe data into epochs. We have chosen epochs as our units of measurement in order to delimitate the beginning and the end of an activity. Epochs reflect consecutive time windows and thus are suitable for this purpose. \n\nWe first split our data into epochs of 128 samples. \nEach epoch spans 2.56 seconds of signal.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# **Time domain features**\n\nWe obtained statistics from signals.\n\nOur time domain features include location measures, spread measures, and histogram shape descriptors.\n\n**Common statistics:**\n* Mean - investigating the signal amplitude\n* SD - spread around the mean\n* Median - adds robustness to outliers\n* Min & Max - can help investigate spikes in the signal\n* Range - amplitude spread measure\n* Covariance - investigates how signals in different directions varied together in the 3D-space. helps distinguish movement across space.\n* IQR - adds robustness to outliers\n* Quantiles - another shape feature\n* Skew - asymmetry in the shape\n* Kurtosis - severity of the tailedness of the signal\n\n**Other statistics:**\n* Lagged correlation - computes the correlation between x and a time shifted y. Helps investigate temporal dependencies in the signal.\n* Power - average squared amplitude of the signal, indicating how much it deviates from 0. Can help distinguish the intensity of signals. \n* Entropy - measure of average uncertainty regarding the potential states of a signal, higher entropy indicating more unpredictability in the signal's patterns. \n* Signal energy - total power of the samples. Sum of squares formula used to estimate \"intensity\" of the activity, which can be used for distinguishing walking from\n* Sign changes - counts how many times a signal changes its sign (from + to -),and can help distinguish lying down from standing.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Helper functions\nmost_common_value = function(x) {\n    counts = table(x, useNA='no')\n    most_frequent = which.max(counts)\n    return(names(most_frequent))\n}\n\n## Feature functions (time domain)\n\n# Lagged correlation\nlagged_cor = function(x, y=x, lag=0) {\n    r_lagged = cor(x, dplyr::lag(y, lag), use='pairwise')\n    return(r_lagged)\n}\n\n# Entropy\nentropy = function(x, nbreaks = nclass.Sturges(x)) {\n    r = range(x)\n    x_binned = findInterval(x, seq(r[1], r[2], len = nbreaks))\n    h = tabulate(x_binned, nbins = nbreaks)\n    p = h/sum(h)\n    -sum(p[p>0] * log(p[p>0]))\n}\n\n# Power \npower = function(x) {\n    power = mean(x^2)\n    return(power)\n}\n\n#IQR \ninterquartile_range = function(x) {\n    return(IQR(x, na.rm=T))\n}\n\n# Signal energy\nsignal_energy = function(x) {\n    return(sum(x^2)/length(x)) \n}\n\n# Sign changes\nsign_changes = function(x) {\n    sum(diff(sign(x)) != 0, na.rm = TRUE) \n}\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.192366Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.193809Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.219085Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.217308Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":5},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We added a variable to distinguish epochs from signal samples. For each epoch, we extracted all statistical features and stored them in a new file.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# **Spectral domain features**\nFor the spectral features, we again split the data into epochs. For each epoch, we computed a spectrum. We combined the three signals in the three-dimensional space, and used spectrum() to calculate the intensity of each signal. Frequency marks the number of oscillations per time unit.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"\n# Step 1 + 2: compute spectra for each epoch\nuser_spect_df <- user_df |>\n  mutate(epoch = sampleid %/% 128) |>\n  reframe({\n    sp <- spectrum(cbind(X1, X2, X3), span = 15, plot = FALSE)\n     tibble(\n      freq  = sp$freq,      # cycles per sample\n      spec1 = sp$spec[, 1],\n      spec2 = sp$spec[, 2],\n      spec3 = sp$spec[, 3]\n    )\n  },.by = epoch)\n\nuser_spect_df |> head()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.221823Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.223299Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.856157Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.854333Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"<table class=\"dataframe\">\n<caption>A tibble: 6 × 5</caption>\n<thead>\n\t<tr><th scope=col>epoch</th><th scope=col>freq</th><th scope=col>spec1</th><th scope=col>spec2</th><th scope=col>spec3</th></tr>\n\t<tr><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n\t<tr><td>0</td><td>0.0078125</td><td>0.01716233</td><td>0.011428361</td><td>0.3161887</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>0</td><td>0.0156250</td><td>0.01842406</td><td>0.010417538</td><td>0.3160508</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>0</td><td>0.0234375</td><td>0.01934893</td><td>0.010119308</td><td>0.3173716</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>0</td><td>0.0312500</td><td>0.02035657</td><td>0.009166670</td><td>0.3153399</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>0</td><td>0.0390625</td><td>0.02456786</td><td>0.008787336</td><td>0.2901735</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>0</td><td>0.0468750</td><td>0.03135924</td><td>0.008796216</td><td>0.2338889</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n","text/markdown":"\nA tibble: 6 × 5\n\n| epoch &lt;dbl&gt; | freq &lt;dbl&gt; | spec1 &lt;dbl&gt; | spec2 &lt;dbl&gt; | spec3 &lt;dbl&gt; |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 0 | 0.0078125 | 0.01716233 | 0.011428361 | 0.3161887 |\n| 0 | 0.0156250 | 0.01842406 | 0.010417538 | 0.3160508 |\n| 0 | 0.0234375 | 0.01934893 | 0.010119308 | 0.3173716 |\n| 0 | 0.0312500 | 0.02035657 | 0.009166670 | 0.3153399 |\n| 0 | 0.0390625 | 0.02456786 | 0.008787336 | 0.2901735 |\n| 0 | 0.0468750 | 0.03135924 | 0.008796216 | 0.2338889 |\n\n","text/latex":"A tibble: 6 × 5\n\\begin{tabular}{lllll}\n epoch & freq & spec1 & spec2 & spec3\\\\\n <dbl> & <dbl> & <dbl> & <dbl> & <dbl>\\\\\n\\hline\n\t 0 & 0.0078125 & 0.01716233 & 0.011428361 & 0.3161887\\\\\n\t 0 & 0.0156250 & 0.01842406 & 0.010417538 & 0.3160508\\\\\n\t 0 & 0.0234375 & 0.01934893 & 0.010119308 & 0.3173716\\\\\n\t 0 & 0.0312500 & 0.02035657 & 0.009166670 & 0.3153399\\\\\n\t 0 & 0.0390625 & 0.02456786 & 0.008787336 & 0.2901735\\\\\n\t 0 & 0.0468750 & 0.03135924 & 0.008796216 & 0.2338889\\\\\n\\end{tabular}\n","text/plain":"  epoch freq      spec1      spec2       spec3    \n1 0     0.0078125 0.01716233 0.011428361 0.3161887\n2 0     0.0156250 0.01842406 0.010417538 0.3160508\n3 0     0.0234375 0.01934893 0.010119308 0.3173716\n4 0     0.0312500 0.02035657 0.009166670 0.3153399\n5 0     0.0390625 0.02456786 0.008787336 0.2901735\n6 0     0.0468750 0.03135924 0.008796216 0.2338889"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":6},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"* Mean frequency of signal - first step at investigating the shape of the spectrum\n* Dominant frequency of signal - shows the frequency with the highest power\n* SD of signal - captures frequency spread\n* Spectral entropy - entropy of power spectrum\n* Frequency variance - variability of spectral distribution\n* Spectral Bandpower High - energy in a specific frequency band\n* Spectral energy - calculates how much power the signal has. Can be used to distinguish the low and high spectral energy periods (ex. lying vs running)\n* Spectrum spread - the spread of power around the dominant frequency","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Feature functions (frequency domain)\nmean_freq = function(freq, spec) {\n    delta_f = freq[2]-freq[1]  # gap size between frequencies\n    normalizing_constant = sum(spec * delta_f) # ≈ ∫S(f)df\n    mean_freq = sum(freq * spec * delta_f) / normalizing_constant\n    return(mean_freq)\n}\n\n# SD\nspec_sd = function(x) {\n    s = spectrum(x, log = 'n', plot = FALSE)\n    df = s$freq[2] - s$freq[1]\n    sbar = sum(s$freq * s$spec * df)\n    svar = sum((s$freq - sbar)^2 * s$spec * df)\n    sd = sqrt(svar)\n    return(sd)\n}\n\n# Spectral Skew \nspec_skew = function(x, nbreaks = nclass.Sturges(x)) {\n    s = spectrum(x, log = 'n', plot = FALSE)\n    df = s$freq[2] - s$freq[1]\n    sbar = sum(s$freq * s$spec * df)\n    svar = sum((s$freq - sbar)^2 * s$spec * df)\n    sd = sqrt(svar)\n    skew = sum((s$freq - sbar)^3 * s$spec * df) / (svar^1.5)\n    return(skew)\n}\n\n# Spectral Kurtosis \nspec_kurt = function(x, nbreaks = nclass.Sturges(x)) {\n    s = spectrum(x, log = 'n', plot = FALSE)\n    df = s$freq[2] - s$freq[1]\n    sbar = sum(s$freq * s$spec * df)\n    svar = sum((s$freq - sbar)^2 * s$spec * df)\n    kurt = sum((s$freq - sbar) ^4 * s$spec * df) / (svar^2)\n    return(kurt)\n}\n\n# Spread of the spectrum\nspectrum_spread = function(freq, spec) {\n    mean_freq = mean_freq(freq, spec) # obtains the mean frequency from another function\n    freqvar = sum((freq-mean_freq)^2 * spec * diff(freq)[1]) \n    freq_sd = sqrt(freqvar)\n    return(freq_sd)\n}\n\n# Frequency variance\ns = spectrum(user_spect_df, plot = FALSE)\nmeanfreq = sum(s$freq * s$spec * diff(s$freq)[1])\nfreqvar = function(x) {\n    s = spectrum(x, log = 'n', plot = FALSE)\n    fv = sum((s$freq-meanfreq)^2 * s$spec * diff(s$freq)[1])\n    return(fv)\n}\n\n# Spectral Bandpower High\nlibrary(broom)\nspec_bands = function(x) {\n    s = spectrum(ts(x, deltat = 1/128), span = 7, plot = FALSE)\n    bands = seq(0, max(s$freq), len = 30)\n    df = s %>%\n    tidy() %>%\n    mutate(band = findInterval(freq, bands)) %>%\n    group_by(band) %>%\n    summarise(\n        band_peak_freq = freq[which.max(spec)],\n        band_power = mean(spec),\n        .groups = 'drop')\n    return(df$band[which.max(df$band_power)])\n}\n\n# Spectral Entropy \nspec_entropy = function(x, nbreaks = nclass.Sturges(x)) {\n    s = spectrum(x, log = 'n', plot = FALSE)\n    h = s$spec\n    h <- h[!is.na(h)]\n    p = h/sum(h)\n    -sum(p[p>0] * log(p[p>0]))\n}\n\n# Spectral Energy \nspec_energy = function(freq, spec) {\n    delta_f = freq[2] - freq[1]     \n    sum(spec * delta_f)            \n}","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.859074Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-24T18:02:07.860599Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-24T18:02:08.029675Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-24T18:02:08.027643Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":7},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Putting it all together\nWe now define a function that extracts all Time domain and Frequency domain features. This function takes the file name as input and carries out all the functions created above on the dataset.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"list.files(\"./RawData/Train/\", pattern = \"^acc\")\nlist.files(\"./RawData/Train/\", pattern = \"^gyro\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-24T18:02:08.032428Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-24T18:02:08.033915Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-24T18:02:08.055575Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-24T18:02:08